he small farm where he and his mother live.  One night some strange half-snake people come and kidnap her.  Riven, of course, goes after her, but before he leaves, a girl (name?) who has a crush on him gives him a mysterious sword with a dark blue stone in the pommel.  When Riven gets to a town on the north coast of Denalla he learns who the snake-people are (Nagas or Naugas, I'm not sure which), why they took the Princess, and, most importantly, the secret of his sword.  Maybe I'll tell you guys more, but I'll leave there for now and let you crit me to death,yo. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :smokin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smokin.gif ALT=":smokin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=emmapeel1601>emmapeel1601</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.geocities.com/garaigh/emma2.txt" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/29/03 7:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1035.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/garaigh/buddy2.txt height=127 width=107></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: me first fantasy story-crits!</span><hr size=1> looks fairly interesting so far. <br>
here's a few things that occurred to me as i read it. (due to the vagueness of the outline i may say things that you've already considered but you can feel free to say &quot;oh, i thought of that already.&quot;) <br>
<br>
first off, who is this second girl and is she like a best friend? you know, the one the guy is always telling all his problems to? the one who is secretly in love with Riven and can't tell him because she knows his heart lies elsewhere? does she come back into the story or is she there just to give him this mysterious sword?<br>
<br>
second, is the princess an annoying character? that's always cool when the object of the hero's affection turns out to be not as perfect as he thought. not that she has to be snotty or mean, just it makes things more interesting for the heroine to be strong-willed and hard to get along with. <br>
<br>
three, it kind of sounds like the people who kidnap the princess aren't necessarily evil (although i could have misread your intention there. that bit's pretty vague.) but let me tell you that there needs to be an obvious villain in the story somewhere. you can foil expectations by making the reader assume that the snake-people are evil and then bringing out another true villain. or you can let the readers know that they aren't evil and create tension because you (the reader) know that something big and tragic will happen if the confusion isn't cleared up. (Timothy Zahn wrote a great trilogy where he used that method. the humans and the aliens had inadvertantly misunderstood each other and were preparing to engage in a galactic war. the reader begins to guess what's really going on and is left in suspense waiting to see if the characters will figure it out in time.) <br>
<br>
btw, i don't know how old you are, but if you're sixteen or over i would suggest reading the first Song of Fire and Ice book by George R. R. Martin, A Game of Thrones. he does a good job of writing about multiple young characters ranging in age from about six or seven to fourteen/fifteen. his writing is rather &quot;adult&quot; though (some graphic nudity, violence) so if you are still young then you might want to wait. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
anyway, this looks interesting. keep fleshing out the idea and see what happens. <br>
